body:
Add a PropertySet member with wrong type for Value1, no error send out.

```
        try
        {
            add-member -InputObject a PropertySet Name ImNotACollection
            Throw "Execution OK"
        }
        catch
        {
            $_.FullyQualifiedErrorId | Should Be "ConvertToFinalInvalidCastException,Microsoft.PowerShell.Commands.AddMemberCommand"
        }
```

comments.body:
I ran this on full Windows PowerShell, and get "Execution OK":

``` powershell
PS C:\Users\andschwa> Describe "Test" {
>>         $ErrorActionPreference = “Stop”
>>         try
>>         {
>>             add-member -InputObject a PropertySet Name ImNotACollection
>>             Throw "Execution OK"
>>         }
>>         catch
>>         {
>>             $_.FullyQualifiedErrorId | Should Be "ConvertToFinalInvalidCastException,Microsoft.PowerShell.Commands.AddMemberCommand"
>>         }
>> }
Describing Test
 [-] Error occurred in Describe block 10ms
   Expected string length 81 but was 12. Strings differ at index 0.
   Expected: {ConvertToFinalInvalidCastException,Microsoft.PowerShell.Commands.AddMemberCommand}
   But was:  {Execution OK}
   -----------^
   At C:\Program Files\WindowsPowerShell\Modules\Pester\3.3.5\Functions\Assertions\Should.ps1:92 char:17
```

Or even more simply:

``` powershell
add-member -InputObject a PropertySet Name ImNotACollection
```

And no error.

@JamesWTruher Is this supposed to throw an error? I could not get it to do so on stock Windows PowerShell.
